Pension funds and long shadows
2019 was a huge anniversary year in the history of pension funds in Iceland.
Officials had, of course, received a pension from the Danish king every street from 19. century, but in 1919 a pension fund was established for officials that eventually became the pension fund of all civil servants.
The basis for the current pension funds for general wage earners was then laid by collective agreements in the labour market in 1969, which provided for employment-related pension funds with compulsory membership and full fund collection from the beginning of 1970.
In 1974, laws were passed on the basis of these agreements and the pension system continued to grow thereafter.
The wage-earnery pension system was not the only radical change that the 20th-century labour movement propelled with its wage struggle.
Unemployment insurance had been similarly received in historic strikes in 1955, and the association also gradually received its demands for sick leave rights and sickness funds, significant vacation rights, shortening of working hours, housing reform and other important issues.
All these rights cost a great and rigorous struggle, but proved, in retrospect, a much greater and more permanent benefit than the increase in the number of coins in the wage envelope, which disappeared as hard in the inflation period that characterised the period after the war and until 1990, as many remember.
The prelude to the establishment of general pension funds in 1969 was both long and complicated.
Although it was finally agreed that the funds would in fact be the property of the fund members, the union movement had to accept that their boards should be composed of representatives of employers and fund members on equal terms.
In the years following the establishment of the funds, the demand for the majority of workers on the board of the funds was often discussed in the unions of employees, but it never succeeded, and therefore we are still left with the abnormal arrangement that the representatives of the fund members are not in the majority on the boards of the funds.
Article 36 of Act No. 129/1997 on compulsory insurance of pension rights and the activities of pension funds is a discussion of the investment policy of the funds.
Item 1 states that “the pension fund shall be guided by the interests of the fund members.”
Item 5 also states: “A pension fund shall set ethical standards in investments.”
The shareholders' policy of the Traders' Pension Fund includes, inter alia, the following provisions, following the aforementioned legal provisions:
The Pension Fund is a member of the United Nations Principles for Responsible Investment, along with many of the largest pension funds and institutional investors in the West and in Europe.
The rules discuss how emphasis on environmental and social issues as well as good corporate governance can contribute to improved investment performance of portfolios.
This combines the interests of investors and the objectives of society in a broader context.
LV considers it important that companies, especially those listed on the stock market, adopt a public policy on: to maintain good corporate governance for social responsibility and environmental issues.
Gildi Pension Fund, which is one of the largest funds in Iceland, has adopted a “policy for responsible investment” and contains provisions of a similar nature.
This is all recalled here as an introduction to the latest fashion of the Icelandic language, “Shadow management”.
Since the word is new in the case, it is not expected that it has been fully defined, but it seems to me that the following definition is now “most taken”: Shadow management is when a union leader says in the media that he intends to send representatives of the union to the board of a pension fund a recommendation or instructions on how to take a stand in a particular case.
If they do not follow the recommendation, they will be removed from the board at the earliest convenience.
If the leader does not take this to the media and does not talk about dismissal, however, it is not “shadow management” as such communication between people is of course always in the financial world as elsewhere.
I'll leave the reader to think about which way he finds "shadier."
There are, in particular, two people who have tried to formulate this definition at the time of writing, on the morning of Saturday, July 25, 2020.
Hörður Ægisson journalist at Fréttablaðið and Ásgeir Jónsson, Governor of the Central Bank of Iceland, are present.
The occasion for both was born after Icelandair CEO Bogi Nils Bogason had stated his intention to terminate the company's agreements with flight attendants and flight attendants (resign them), and Ragnar Þór Ingólfsson, chairman of the Reykjavík Chamber of Commerce, sent out the recommendation to the company's representatives on the board of the Traders' Pension Fund not to support the fund's potential purchase of shares in the company, otherwise they might be dismissed.
Some time later, Bogi Nils withdrew his decision and subsequently Ragnar Þór followed the same path with his recommendations, which were of course based on Bogi's decision.
Nevertheless, Hörður and Ásgeir saw reason to speak about the matter in the Friday issue of Fréttablaðið with big words about shadow control, violations of the law and a strong need for changes in the law.
There, a small thuff was indeed supposed to roll a heavy load, even though the blessed tuff had been in a subjunctive manner and also been quickly wiped out.
Since the issue is important, let's consider the subject itself at the end.
I explained above the points in the Act on Pension Funds pertaining to this matter.
These matters entail that the boards of the Fund must protect the interests of fund members and have ethical criteria in investments, and these issues are further elaborated in the articles of association of both Gildi and the Pension Fund of Retailers, as I mentioned.
However, pension funds should NOT look only at short-term profitability considerations in their investments.
This would be a very dangerous policy and does not have to look for examples of this in the past, as large loans of banks and funds have flowed to immoral adventurers and environmental disasters, with disastrous consequences.
