Will the Olympic fire be the light at the end of the tunnel?
After the final decision had been made to postpone the Olympics, an event that only world wars have plagued to date, the president of the International Olympic Committee said that the famous Olympic fire would be "the light at the end of the tunnel," presumably referring to the coronavirus pandemic that the world is now going through together.
Achievement workers have years to prepare and authorities in Japan will add to the cost of the delay.
Everyone has a header, but there's a lot at stake.
When it was announced that Tokyo in Japan would be the venue for this year's Olympic Games, the Japanese delegates' cheers were genuine.
They wept and laughed alternately, as Tokyo had applied to host the 2016 Games, but that time it bowed to a lower level for Rio in Brazil.
This time Tokyo City and Japan should bathe in the world's attention.
The Games are scheduled to take place from July 24 to 9. August but has been postponed for a year and instead starts on 23 July 2021 and ends on 8. August.
If the Games are not held, if the coronavirus still becomes too much of a threat, the Games will be cancelled.
No one wants to think that way to the end.
Olympics are no ordinary sports competition.
Nothing is saved, the show should always be spectacular and strive to top the last play.
The choice of a city for the Olympic Games is based on the selection committee's assessment of the promotions of the cities.
The more spectacular the presentation—the greater the chance of receiving the prize.
Tokyo spent 150 million dollars trying to host the 2016 Olympics, or over 20 billion.
The second time, when the 2020 Games were applied for, 75 million dollars, about ten billion ISK, was put into the presentation.
By 2013, when it was decided that Tokyo would receive the Games this year, the Japanese authorities had already spent 30 billion ISK on the project.
But that amount is only a drop in the ocean considering how much it costs to build Olympic villages, stadiums and generally strengthen the country's infrastructure to handle such tournaments, prepare it and hold the games themselves.
Japanese organisers have said the Tokyo Olympics, which should have been running these days but have been postponed by a year due to the coronavirus, would have cost US$12.6 billion.
However, a report from the Japan Auditor General published at the end of last year stated that the cost was nearly double that number.
It is likely that the cost of postponing the Games will not be fully assessed, but it has been estimated that it can cost between two and six billion dollars in addition to the original cost.
The total cost for the Japanese Olympic Committee and Japanese taxpayers could therefore run between 15 and 30 billion dollars.
It is such a high number that all tax revenues of the Icelandic state would only be sufficient for almost half of the Olympics, given the lowest possible cost.
Olympics are an event of such magnitude that they have often become the subject of economists, who try to examine the numbers and look at the benefits and benefits of the Games.
In the shortest possible term, it seems that quite a few people have come to the conclusion that the impact of the Olympics is less than so positive for the economy of the cities that keep them.
There are some short-term effects, for example, the number of jobs is greatly increased in the short term, but in the long term cities tend to be left with debt tails and the high operating costs of little-used structures.
Rio, Brazil, is facing significant debts due to the 2016 Games and has been struggling to cover the maintenance of all the major sports facilities built before the Games.
Figures have been reviewed after the 2012 London Games, where it has been found that only 10 percent of those who got professionally linked to the Olympics in the city were unemployed before.
It means that we didn’t talk about new jobs, except for a little while.
In general, cities have not come out of the Olympics particularly well because of the sliding costs associated with the structures built for the Games.
The benefits, however, are often considered to be increased traffic of tourists who want to visit the Olympic cities following the Games, which, however, is highly uncertain about the 2021 Games.
It is also uncertain whether it will be possible to accept all the crowds that usually attend the Games.
The main thing, however, is the honor that the cities have to be chosen, but it is difficult to estimate for money.
